# Valgrind suppression for the U3 ScriptEngine swap-test (x3d_quickjs_swap).
#
# JUSTIFICATION (minimal + benign): the vendored Duktape 2.7.0 engine's bytecode
# compiler calls realloc(ptr, 0) when a parse-pass buffer is reset to length 0
# (duk__reset_func_for_pass2 / duk__reset_labels_to_length). C standard makes
# realloc(p,0) implementation-defined, and modern Valgrind (>=3.x) flags it as
# "realloc() with size 0". It is NOT a leak and NOT a use of freed/uninitialised
# memory — the swap-test itself reports "in use at exit: 0 bytes ... no leaks are
# possible". This is a pre-existing property of the vendored C engine (the same
# context fires in the long-standing x3d_ecmascript_backend_test) and is wholly
# inside Duktape's own allocator path, never in the seam or test code. The
# QuickJS backend produces no such report. Suppressed so the swap-test runs
# valgrind-clean without masking any real error (the context is pinned tightly to
# Duktape's realloc wrapper + the two reset call sites).
{
   duktape-realloc-size-zero-pass2-reset
   Memcheck:ReallocZero
   fun:realloc
   fun:duk_default_realloc_function
   fun:duk_heap_mem_realloc_indirect
   fun:duk_hbuffer_resize
   ...
   fun:duk__parse_func_body
}
